Schema inference versus an explicit schema.

You have two choices when reading text formats like csv and json. You can let Spark infer the schema, or you can declare it yourself. They feel interchangeable on a small file, but on real data they are not.

Inference is the convenient one, and it is fine for exploratory work. The catch is that inference triggers a separate scan over the data before your real query even starts. On a hundred-gigabyte csv that is a non-trivial pre-job, paid every single time you read.

There is a subtler danger too. Inference is a best-effort guess, and the guess can drift. Picture a credit-limit column that read as a decimal yesterday. Today one row contains the text N-A, and now Spark infers the whole column as a string. Downstream, every sum over that column quietly fails. Nothing told you the type changed.

An explicit schema removes both problems. No pre-scan, so it is fast, and the types are guaranteed because you declared them. To put it plainly — inference for exploring, explicit schemas for production. Always.
